obo:ECO_0007695  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_4024  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 2A and B: Frequency of spontaneous mEPSC activity was significantly\nlower in PS1mut neurons than in PS1 WT neurons and non-transgenic cells.\nFigure 2D: the number of vesicles released during an EPSC was determined and found to be significantly lower in the case of PS1mut neuron.\n\nAmount of RRP vesicles was calculated by dividing the total charge of the transient current component (Figure 3A) after application of hypertonic sucrose by the charge of a single mEPSC measured from the same cell.\nFigure 3B: Neurons from PS1mut mice showed significantly less releasable vesicles in their RRP compared with neurons from nontransgenic and PS1 wild-type mice.\nFigure 3C: Vesicular release probability was not different between PS1 mutant, WT and non-transgenic neurons.\n\nIn summary, these results indicate that PS1 does not affect the vesicular release probability. The decreases in synaptic responses in PS1mut can be attributed to the decrease in RRP in the presynapse.\n\nThe term 'regulation of synaptic vesicle cycle' was used due to a lack of evidence on the mechanism by which PSEN1 mutation causes a reduction in RRP and number of vesicles that are released during an EPSC.. Experimental description: The parent PS1 transgenic mice (wild-type human PS1 and human mutant PS1[A246E]) were generated by microinjection of mini-gene constructs containing PS1 cDNA in a mouse Thy1 gene cassette into prenuclear embryos as described in Moechars et al (1999)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2020-12-08" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4024" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

